'''Ethan Chidiebere Nwaneri''' (born 21 March 2007) is an English professional [[association football|footballer]] who plays as an [[Midfielder#Attacking midfielder|attacking midfielder]] or [[Midfielder#Winger|winger]] for [[Ligue 1]] club [[Olympique de Marseille|Marseille]], on loan from [[Premier League]] club [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]], and the [[England national under-21 football team|England U21 national team]].

Born in [[North London]], Nwaneri joined [[Arsenal F.C. Under-21s and Academy|Arsenal's Academy]] at the age of eight. He made his Premier League debut against [[Brentford F.C.|Brentford]] on 18 September 2022, becoming the youngest player to appear in the top flight of English football, at 15 years and 181 days old.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Ames |first=Nick |date=18 September 2022 |title=Arsenal return to top spot as Fábio Vieira strike seals win at Brentford |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2022/sep/18/brentford-arsenal-premier-league-match-report |access-date=18 September 2022 |website=The Guardian}}</ref><ref name=":1">{{Cite news |last=Jacob |first=Gary |date=18 September 2022 |title=Ethan Nwaneri: Arsenal's 15-year-old becomes youngest top-flight player |work=The Times |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/ethan-nwaneri-arsenals-15-year-old-becomes-youngest-top-flight-player-v2ln00f9v |url-access=subscription |access-date=18 September 2022}}</ref>

==Early life and education==
Ethan Nwaneri was born on 21 March 2007 at [[Whittington Hospital]] in [[Islington, London]], to a [[Nigerians|Nigerian]] father of [[Igbo people|Igbo]] origin, and an [[English people|English]]-[[French people|French]] mother.<ref name="worldfootball" />  He attended St John's Senior School in [[Enfield, London|Enfield]], North London.<ref>{{Cite web |title='I gave Ethan Nwaneri a scholarship in eight minutes – Arsenal have someone very special' {{!}} Football {{!}} Sport {{!}} Express.co.uk |url=https://www.express.co.uk/sport/football/1970048/ethan-nwaneri-arsenal-st-johns-senior-school/amp |access-date=2025-09-14 |website=www.express.co.uk}}</ref>

==Club career==
===Early career===
Nwaneri joined [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] at the age of eight. By the age of 14, he was already playing for their under-18 side.  Nwaneri played alongside friend and teammate [[Myles Lewis-Skelly]] at the academy.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/6221621/2025/03/24/arsenal-myles-lewis-skelly-ethan-nwaneri/|date=23 March 2025|first=Off|last=Handbrake|website=The Athletic|title=The rise of Myles Lewis-Skelly and Ethan Nwaneri: 'It's a beautiful thing they've come through together'|language=en}}</ref>

===Arsenal===
====2022–23 season====
Nwaneri started the 2022–23 season playing for Arsenal under-18s, but he quickly advanced to the club's under-21 side.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Meyers|first=Billy|date=3 September 2022|title=Journalist claims "Unbelievable" 15-year-old will join Arsenal Under-21 side for today's game|url=https://www.hitc.com/en-gb/2022/09/03/journalist-claims-unbelievable-15-year-old-will-join-arsenal-under-21-side-for-todays-game/|access-date=18 September 2022|website=hitc.com}}</ref> Having made a sole appearance in the [[2022–23 Professional U21 Development League#Premier League 2|2022–23 Premier League 2]], he joined the first team for training in September,<ref>{{Cite web |date=18 September 2022|title=Mikel Arteta calls 15-year-old up to first-team training|url=https://dailycannon.com/2022/09/ethan-nwaneri-first-team-training/|access-date=18 September 2022|publisher=dailycannon.com}}</ref> and made his first senior matchday squad on 18 September when he was named as a substitute for the [[Premier League]] match against [[Brentford F.C.|Brentford]].<ref name="nwaneri bbc.com">{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/62946036 |title=Arsenal: Ethan Nwaneri, 15, becomes youngest Premier League player |last=Johnston |first=Neil |date=18 September 2022 |publisher=[[BBC Sport]] |access-date=19 September 2022 }}</ref> Coming off the bench to replace [[Fábio Vieira (footballer, born 2000)|Fábio Vieira]] in second-half stoppage time, he became the youngest player to ever appear in the Premier League at the age of 15 years and 181 days – breaking the record previously held by [[Harvey Elliott]],<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.skysports.com/football/brentford-vs-arsenal/report/464706 |title=Brentford 0–3 Arsenal: Fabio Vieira scores first Gunners goal as Mikel Arteta's side go top again |last=Wright |first=Nick |date=19 September 2022 |publisher=Sky Sports |access-date=19 September 2022 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://talksport.com/football/1197739/arsenal-ethan-nwaneri-bench-brentford-15-premier-league-record/ |title=Arsenal's 15-year-old wonderkid Ethan Nwaneri smashes Liverpool star's Premier League record with debut against Brentford and wasn't born when Gunners reached Champions League final |last=Fordham |first=Josh |date=19 September 2022 |publisher=Talksport |access-date=19 September 2022 }}</ref> and the all-time English top-flight record held since August 1964 by former [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]] goalkeeper [[Derek Forster]], by three days.<ref name=":1" /><ref name="nwaneri arsenal.com">{{cite web |url=https://www.arsenal.com/news/nwaneri-enters-record-books |title=Nwaneri enters the record books |last=James |first=Josh |date=20 September 2022 |publisher=Arsenal F.C. |access-date=20 September 2022 }}</ref> He also became Arsenal's youngest-ever player in any competition, breaking the previous record of 16 years and 177 days, set by [[Cesc Fàbregas]] in the [[2003–04 Football League Cup|2003–04 League Cup]].<ref name="nwaneri arsenal.com"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/sports/soccer/arsenals-ethan-nwaneri-becomes-youngest-epl-player-at-15/2022/09/18/38bcf900-3763-11ed-b8af-0a04e5dc3db6_story.html|title= Arsenal's Ethan Nwaneri becomes youngest EPL player at 15|access-date=18 September 2022|website=washingtonpost.com}}</ref> In the post-match press conference, manager [[Mikel Arteta]] explained that they had to name Nwaneri and two other under-21 players on the bench because the first team had several injuries, especially the injury of midfielder and captain [[Martin Ødegaard]], and a "gut feeling" was behind his decision to send Nwaneri on.<ref name="nwaneri bbc.com"/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.arsenal.com/mikel-arteta-post-match-press-conference-ethan-nwaneri-premier-league-brentford |title=Arteta on why he gave Ethan Nwaneri debut |date=18 September 2022 |publisher=Arsenal F.C. |access-date=19 September 2022 }}</ref><ref name="nwaneri goal.com">{{cite web |url=https://www.goal.com/en-us/news/why-did-arsenal-give-nwaneri-record-breaking-debut-arteta-explains-gut-feeling/blt2c2197ecbbb36086 |title=Why did Arsenal give Nwaneri record-breaking debut? Arteta explains 'gut feeling' |last=Watts |first=Charles |date=18 September 2022 |website=goal.com |access-date=19 September 2022 }}</ref>

In June 2023, with his schoolboy terms ending, Nwaneri agreed to a new deal with Arsenal on scholarship terms with an agreement for a professional contract upon his seventeenth birthday on 21 March 2024.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/4651468/2023/06/29/ethan-nwaneri-arsenal-contract-transfer/|title= Arsenal prospect Ethan Nwaneri commits future to club|first=David|last=Ornstein|website=The Athletic|date=29 June 2023|access-date=29 June 2023}}</ref>

====2023–24 season====
Nwaneri played as a substitute in the 2023–24 season in the Premier League in Arsenal's 6–0 win away against [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]], coming on in the 77th minute. In the post-match press conference, Arteta mentioned "the players on the bench whispering to bring Ethan on, which is a great thing to hear".<ref>{{Cite web |date=17 February 2024 |title=Every word from Mikel's post West Ham presser |url=https://www.arsenal.com/news/every-word-mikels-post-west-ham-presser |access-date=12 February 2024 |website=Every word from Mikel's post West Ham presser}}</ref>

====2024–25 season====
On 25 September 2024, Nwaneri scored his first senior goals when he netted a brace against [[Bolton Wanderers F.C.|Bolton Wanderers]] in the third round of the [[2024–25 EFL Cup#Third round|EFL Cup]], helping the Gunners to a 5–1 victory.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Wright |first=Stephen |date=25 September 2024 |title=Report: Arsenal 5–1 Bolton Wanderers |url=https://www.arsenal.com/fixture/arsenal/2024-Sep-25/arsenal-bolton-wanderers-match-report |access-date=25 September 2024 |website=[[Arsenal F.C.]]}}</ref> He scored an outside-the-box shot against [[Preston North End F.C.|Preston North End]] in the following round.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2024-10-30 |title=Report: Preston North End 0–3 Arsenal |url=https://www.arsenal.com/fixture/arsenal/2024-Oct-30/preston-north-end-0-3-arsenal-match-report |access-date=2024-10-31 |website=Report: Preston North End 0–3 Arsenal |language=en}}</ref> He scored his first goal in the [[Premier League]] on 23 November in Arsenal's 3–0 win home against [[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]] after getting subbed on in the 82nd-minute.<ref>{{Cite web |date =2024-11-13 |title=Nwaneri makes history with first Premier League goal |url=https://www.premierleague.com/news/4175103 |website=Premier League|language=en}}</ref> This made him the ninth-youngest goalscorer in the league's history at 17 years, 247 days old.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Furniss |first=Matt |date=2024-11-23 |title=The Youngest Premier League Scorers |url=https://theanalyst.com/na/2024/11/youngest-premier-league-scorers |access-date=2024-11-23 |website=Opta Analyst |language=en}}</ref>

On 4 January 2025, Nwaneri scored in a 1–1 draw against [[Brighton & Hove Albion F.C.|Brighton & Hove Albion]], becoming the third player to score at least five goals in a season before turning 18, following [[Michael Owen]] and [[Wayne Rooney]].<ref>{{Cite web |date =2025-01-05 |title=Nwaneri makes history with Arsenal goal at Brighton |url=https://www.premierleague.com/news/4217213 |website=Premier League|language=en}}</ref> Later that month, on 29 January, he netted his first [[UEFA Champions League]] goal, securing a 2–1 away win over [[Girona FC|Girona]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Lowe |first=Sid |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2025/jan/29/girona-arsenal-champions-league-match-report |title=Nwaneri's screamer seals turnaround at Girona as Arsenal ensure spot in last 16 |work=The Guardian |date=29 January 2025 }}</ref> Four days later, on 2 February, Nwaneri scored the fifth and final goal in a 5–1 win over [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]], curling in a stoppage-time strike from just outside the penalty box.<ref>{{cite web |last=Ronay |first=Barney |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2025/feb/02/lewis-kelly-strikes-a-pose-as-haaland-is-riled-and-arsenal-savour-catharsis |title=Lewis-Skelly strikes a pose as Haaland is riled and Arsenal savour catharsis |work=The Guardian |date=2 February 2025 }}</ref> Nwaneri was named [[Man of the Match]] following his performance against [[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester City]], where he hit the woodwork twice and provided an assist for [[Mikel Merino]] in the 2–0 victory. On 4 March, Nwaneri scored the second of seven Arsenal goals away at [[PSV Eindhoven]] in the Champions League Last-16.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.arsenal.com/fixture/arsenal/2025-Mar-04/psv-eindhoven-1-7-arsenal-match-report|title=Report:PSV Eindhoven 1–7 Arsenal|first=Josh|last=James|website=Arsenal.com|language=en|date=4 March 2025}}</ref>

On 19 June 2025, it was announced that Nwaneri was one of six nominees for the PFA Young Player of the Year award.<ref>{{Cite web |date=19 June 2025 |title=PFA Young Player of the Year nominees announced |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/articles/cj4edzw9qxeo |access-date=19 June 2025 |publisher=BBC Sport |language=en-GB}}</ref>

====2025–26 season====
On 8 August 2025, Nwaneri signed a new long-term contract with Arsenal.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.arsenal.com/news/ethan-nwaneri-signs-new-contract |title=Ethan Nwaneri signs new contract |publisher=Arsenal F.C. |date=8 August 2025 }}</ref>

====Loan to Marseille====
On 23 January 2026, Nwaneri was loaned to [[Olympique de Marseille|Marseille]] until the end of the 2025–26 season.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=Olympique de Marseille|url=https://www.om.fr/fr/actualites/4803/equipe-1ere/106496-ethan-nwaneri-est-marseillais|title=Ethan Nwaneri est Marseillais|trans-title=Ethan Nwaneri is at Marseille|date=23 January 2026|access-date=23 January 2026|language=fr}}</ref> The next day, Nwaneri scored 13 minutes into his Marseille debut in a 3–1 victory over [[RC Lens|Lens]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=Marseille 3-1 Lens: Arsenal loanee Ethan Nwaneri scores on Marseille debut |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/live/cz6ynq9p82qt |access-date=2026-01-24 |website=BBC Sport |language=en-GB}}</ref>

==International career==
Nwaneri is eligible to represent [[Nigeria national football team|Nigeria]]  and [[France national football team|France]] through his parents, but has chosen to represent England at youth level.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Guerreiro |first=Adefolahan |title="He's a big talent" – Mikel Arteta praises Arsenal's Nigeria-eligible midfield gem |url=https://soccernet.ng/2024/10/hes-a-big-talent-mikel-arteta-praises-arsenals-nigeria-eligible-midfield-gem.html |access-date=November 24, 2024 |work=Soccernet}}</ref> After starring in qualifying, Nwaneri was named in the [[England national under-17 football team|England]] squad for the [[2023 UEFA European Under-17 Championship]] on 17 May 2023.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Veevers|first=Nicholas|date=17 May 2023|title=England MU17s squad named for EURO Finals|url=https://www.englandfootball.com/articles/2023/May/17/england-mens-under-17-squad-named-for-u17-EURO-in-hungary-20231705|access-date=18 May 2023|website=EnglandFootball.com}}</ref> He scored the winner in the opening match against [[Croatia national under-17 football team|Croatia]] at [[Balmazújvárosi Városi Sportpálya]].<ref>{{Cite web |last=Veevers|first=Nicholas|date=18 May 2023|title=Report: Croatia 0–1 England MU17s|url=https://www.englandfootball.com/articles/2023/May/18/england-mens-under-17s-croatia-u17-euro-match-report-20231805|access-date=18 May 2023|website=EnglandFootball.com}}</ref>

On 2 November 2023, Nwaneri was included in the England squad for the [[2023 FIFA U-17 World Cup]].<ref>{{Cite web |last=Smith|first=Frank|date=2 November 2023|title=England squad for the FIFA U-17 World Cup|url=https://www.englandfootball.com/articles/2023/Nov/02/england-mens-under-17-world-cup-squad-20231102|access-date=13 November 2023|website=EnglandFootball.com}}</ref> He scored his only goal of the tournament in their opening group game against [[New Caledonia national under-17 football team|New Caledonia]] in [[Jakarta]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.espn.co.uk/football/match/_/gameId/688160|title=England v New Caledonia|accessdate=30 December 2023|website=ESPN}}</ref> Nwaneri also played in the other group fixtures against [[Iran national under-17 football team|Iran]] and [[Brazil national under-17 football team|Brazil]].<ref>{{Cite web|accessdate=8 June 2024|title=England 2–1 Iran|date=14 November 2023|url=https://www.espn.co.uk/football/match/_/gameId/688172/iran-u17-england-u17|website=ESPN}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|accessdate=8 June 2024|title=England 1–2 Brazil|date=17 November 2023|url=https://www.espn.co.uk/football/match/_/gameId/688184|website=ESPN}}</ref> He came off the bench as a substitute during their round of sixteen defeat against [[Uzbekistan national under-17 football team|Uzbekistan]].<ref>{{Cite web|accessdate=8 June 2024|title=England 1–2 Uzbekistan|date=22 November 2023|url=https://www.espn.co.uk/football/match/_/gameId/688196/uzbekistan-u17-england-u17|website=ESPN}}</ref>

On 20 May 2024, Nwaneri was included in the England squad for the [[2024 UEFA European Under-17 Championship]].<ref>{{Cite web |last=Veevers|first=Nicholas|date=20 May 2024|title=England MU17s squad named for EURO Finals|url=https://www.englandfootball.com/articles/2024/May/20/england-mens-under-17s-squad-named-for-EURO-Finals-in-cyprus-20242005|access-date=21 May 2024|website=EnglandFootball.com}}</ref> He once again scored in the opening game of the tournament, this time a 4–0 win over [[France national under-17 football team|France]] in [[Larnaca]].<ref>{{Cite web|last=Nottingham|first=Juliet|date=21 May 2024|title=Report: England MU17 4–0 France|url=https://www.englandfootball.com/articles/2024/May/21/england-mu17s-france-euro-match-report-20242105|access-date=21 May 2024|website=EnglandFootball.com|archive-date=21 May 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240521214537/https://www.englandfootball.com/articles/2024/May/21/england-mu17s-france-euro-match-report-20242105|url-status=dead}}</ref> Nwaneri also scored in a group stage victory over [[Spain national under-17 football team|Spain]].<ref>{{Cite web |last=Gibson|first=Thomas|date=27 May 2024|title=Report: England MU17s 3–1 Spain|url=https://www.englandfootball.com/articles/2024/May/27/england-mu17s-spain-EURO-match-report-20242705|access-date=8 June 2024|website=EnglandFootball.com}}</ref> His third and last goal of the competition came in their quarter-final elimination against [[Italy national under-17 football team|Italy]].<ref>{{Cite web |last=Gorrie|first=Jonathan|date=31 May 2024|title=Ethan Nwaneri stunner not enough as England U17 beaten on penalties by Italy|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/sport/football/nwaneri-goal-england-u17-italy-euros-b1161215.html|access-date=8 June 2024|website=Evening Standard}}</ref>

On his 18th birthday, 21 March 2025, Nwaneri made his [[England national under-21 football team|England U21]] debut as a substitute during a 5–3 defeat to [[France national under-21 football team|France]] in [[Lorient]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.englandfootball.com/articles/2025/Mar/21/england-mens-under-21s-france-match-report-live-20252103|title=Report: France 5–3 England MU21s|first=Phil|last=Campbell|date=21 March 2025|accessdate=23 March 2025|website=EnglandFootball.com}}</ref>
Just 3 days later he scored his first goal for England U21 in his first full debut to bring England 4–2 victory against [[Portugal national under-21 football team|Portugal]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11095/13334925/england-u21-4-2-portugal-u21-ethan-nwaneri-marks-his-full-england-under-21s-debut-with-a-goal/|title=Nwaneri marks full England U21 debut with goal in win|date=24 March 2025|accessdate=27 March 2025|website=skysports.com}}</ref>

Nwaneri was selected for England's squad at the [[2025 UEFA European Under-21 Championship]], featuring in all six matches,<ref>{{Cite web |date=2025-10-18 |title=Nwaneri helps England win 2025 U21 Euros |url=https://www.arsenal.com/news/nwaneri-helps-england-win-euro-u21-title |access-date=2025-10-11 |website=Nwaneri helps England win 2025 U21 Euros |language=en}}</ref> including the [[2025 UEFA European Under-21 Championship final|final]] in which the England U21's secured the title for a second consecutive tournament.<ref>{{Cite web |title=England vs Germany LIVE: U21 Euros Final – score, radio, stats & updates |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/live/cz6g18dz2dpt |access-date=2025-06-29 |website=BBC Sport |language=en-GB}}</ref>

On 23 May 2026, it was announced Nwaneri was one of four players (alongside [[Alex Scott (footballer, born 2003)|Alex Scott]], [[Josh King (footballer, born 2007)|Josh King]] and [[Rio Ngumoha]]) that would join the [[England national football team|senior team]] for the squad's preparation camp before the [[2026 FIFA World Cup]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Young England talents to join Three Lions in Florida |url=https://www.englandfootball.com/articles/2026/May/22/young-england-talents-to-join-three-lions-in-florida |website=englandfootball.com |publisher=[[The Football Association]] |date=23 May 2026}}</ref>

